00:23:55.710 --> 00:23:57.709
for women in computing.

00:23:57.709 --> 00:23:59.750
The Google Crisis Response
participate every year

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:03.300
in the Open Source Day where we
work on one of our open source

00:24:03.300 --> 00:24:06.090
tools to try to add features.

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:06.890
So, thank you.

00:24:14.020 --> 00:24:16.540
So if you have any questions,
because I rushed a little bit.

00:24:28.139 --> 00:24:28.680
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:31.740
I was wondering about
the Person Finder.

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:34.950
So I understand that privacy
is not at the top of your head

00:24:34.950 --> 00:24:37.540
when you're in a crisis
and trying to find somebody

00:24:37.540 --> 00:24:41.260
or letting somebody know-- but
what about when you search,

00:24:41.260 --> 00:24:43.860
it comes up a list
of all the people--

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:46.800
how do you approach privacy?

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:47.950
Is it a concern?

00:24:47.950 --> 00:24:50.780
Or have you thought about
sort of doing a matching thing

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:53.899
without having to be
able to see everybody's--

00:24:53.899 --> 00:24:55.440
ALICE BONHOMME-BIAIS:
Yeah, so that's

00:24:55.440 --> 00:24:56.620
a very important question.

00:24:56.620 --> 00:24:58.900
Because as you said,
during a crisis situation,

00:24:58.900 --> 00:25:01.130
people don't necessarily
have privacy in their head.

00:25:01.130 --> 00:25:03.960
So they're ready
to just give all--

00:25:03.960 --> 00:25:06.670
you're looking for someone, so
some people might not realize

00:25:06.670 --> 00:25:08.810
that they put a lot of
information there that

00:25:08.810 --> 00:25:12.310
it's-- yeah, it can hurt them.

00:25:12.310 --> 00:25:15.135
So, for example, when you
enter some information,

00:25:15.135 --> 00:25:16.920
there's some information
we don't display.

00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:21.360
We don't display the date
of birth, for example.

00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:23.550
So we don't display it here.

00:25:23.550 --> 00:25:27.430
There's privacy in terms of
we-- between the first version

00:25:27.430 --> 00:25:31.060
and now, there's been a lot
of things, mainly related

00:25:31.060 --> 00:25:31.680
to privacy.

00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:33.510
And actually, we
work with, there's

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:36.800
a consortium working
on missing people

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:38.710
where there's different
NGOs in there.

00:25:38.710 --> 00:25:41.480
There's the Red Cross, and
we work all together on PFIF

00:25:41.480 --> 00:25:42.080
in particular.

00:25:42.080 --> 00:25:43.190
And privacy is a big one.

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:47.310
So we added for the
records to be expired.

00:25:47.310 --> 00:25:52.690
We also added a way for people
to lock a record in Person

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:55.470
Finder so other people
cannot add information.

00:25:55.470 --> 00:25:58.040
If you create it, you
can also delete it.

00:25:58.040 --> 00:26:00.290
Because unfortunately
we got some people

00:26:00.290 --> 00:26:03.660
that did spam Person Finder
after the earthquake in Japan.

00:26:03.660 --> 00:26:06.540
Some people just
put wrong comments.

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:09.430
You always have people that
will try to abuse the system.

00:26:09.430 --> 00:26:11.750
But my faith in
humanity just got

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:15.440
hurt when I saw that, when I
saw people putting bad comments

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:17.410
and for whatever reason.

00:26:17.410 --> 00:26:19.970
So we are working
on allowing people

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:22.810
to better control their
data, so you can actually

00:26:22.810 --> 00:26:23.850
delete some data.

00:26:23.850 --> 00:26:27.480
You cannot download the
entire data, for example.

00:26:27.480 --> 00:26:30.420
So we try to do
things like this.

00:26:30.420 --> 00:26:32.900
But that's a big concern, yes.

00:26:36.990 --> 00:26:39.754
AUDIENCE: So, also
on the Person Finder.

00:26:39.754 --> 00:26:41.420
I thought it was
really interesting when

00:26:41.420 --> 00:26:43.640
you were speaking, because
I was thinking, well,

00:26:43.640 --> 00:26:45.870
a lot of people-- my name's
very common, for one,

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:47.620
and I know a lot of
people have my name.

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:50.460
And so I was thinking,
gosh, how would you

00:26:50.460 --> 00:26:52.490
do conflict resolution
on something like that?

00:26:52.490 --> 00:26:54.510
Because I imagine
if a family thought

00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:56.370
that they had found
their loved one,

00:26:56.370 --> 00:26:58.286
and then it turned out
they hadn't, that there

00:26:58.286 --> 00:26:59.369
would be so much blowback.

00:26:59.369 --> 00:27:02.180
And it would be just more
hairy than it normally--

00:27:02.180 --> 00:27:04.580
because you make a mistake
normally, it's not a big deal.

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:06.077
But in a crisis
it kind of affects

00:27:06.077 --> 00:27:07.160
people in a different way.

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:09.020
And I was wondering if
you could speak to that.

00:27:09.020 --> 00:27:10.280
ALICE BONHOMME-BIAIS:
Yeah, so that's

00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:12.655
in discussions that we had
internally where we could say,

00:27:12.655 --> 00:27:16.320
oh, we can have some cool
clustering algorithm to cluster

00:27:16.320 --> 00:27:17.290
people together.

00:27:17.290 --> 00:27:22.670
But as you said, the risk if you
miscluster people is very big.

00:27:22.670 --> 00:27:24.230
And we think it's
better for people

00:27:24.230 --> 00:27:26.250
to go over several records.

00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:27.920
And so you have
more description.

00:27:27.920 --> 00:27:29.610
You just only have the names.

00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:32.700
A lot of people would say
that person is about that age,

00:27:32.700 --> 00:27:36.220
and you have black hair or
blonde hair and et cetera.

00:27:36.220 --> 00:27:39.640
And so this way you can know
if that's the same or not,

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:42.290
and this is something that
is hard to do automatically.

00:27:42.290 --> 00:27:45.000
And unless we have
something that is 100%,

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.720
we don't want to take
the risk to do that.

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:49.580
But otherwise you
can actually use

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:51.310
people that will
do that manually.

00:27:51.310 --> 00:27:53.990
So that's in crisis situation,
a lot of people volunteer

00:27:53.990 --> 00:27:54.720
to help.

00:27:54.720 --> 00:27:56.800
So we actually
have a UI where you

00:27:56.800 --> 00:27:58.500
can mark two things
as duplicates

00:27:58.500 --> 00:28:00.320
manually and say these
two are the same.

00:28:00.320 --> 00:28:03.880
But it's done by a human
being and not an algorithm.

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:08.460
AUDIENCE: Thank
you for your talk.

00:28:08.460 --> 00:28:13.550
So speaking personally from our
experience in Sandy, my friends

00:28:13.550 --> 00:28:15.050
and I are really
technically capable

00:28:15.050 --> 00:28:16.920
and you're looking
for ways to help.

00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:20.040
Have you seen-- do you see this
evolving into a coordination

00:28:20.040 --> 00:28:22.890
point for one ways
that developers

00:28:22.890 --> 00:28:25.450
can help either during
a crisis or beyond it

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:28.830
by building tools, or
acquiring information,

00:28:28.830 --> 00:28:33.330
or on the other side,
people who need help?

00:28:33.330 --> 00:28:37.260
Like being a place to
find instead of people,

00:28:37.260 --> 00:28:39.207
but people who need help.

00:28:39.207 --> 00:28:40.290
ALICE BONHOMME-BIAIS: Yes.

00:28:40.290 --> 00:28:43.605
So I think in the past
three, four years,

00:28:43.605 --> 00:28:45.340
the ecosystem is changing a lot.

00:28:45.340 --> 00:28:47.510
So before it was a lot
like, oh, the government

00:28:47.510 --> 00:28:49.700
is on top of things
and this organization.

00:28:49.700 --> 00:28:52.140
And they realize that
it's harder and harder

00:28:52.140 --> 00:28:55.050
to just be everywhere.

00:28:55.050 --> 00:28:58.320
And people locally, they
have a lot of knowledge,

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:00.110
and everyone is ready to help.

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:05.370
And during Sandy, you had Occupy
Sandy was like a great example.

00:29:05.370 --> 00:29:07.660
Things just got
organized and they

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:09.960
use different technology
and all of that.

00:29:09.960 --> 00:29:13.830
Just people volunteering
and getting together.

00:29:13.830 --> 00:29:15.790
And so I think more
and more, so New York

00:29:15.790 --> 00:29:17.960
has-- New York City
in particular--

00:29:17.960 --> 00:29:19.980
they have a sort of a
task force, I think,

00:29:19.980 --> 00:29:22.000
and they do regularly
some hackathon

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.730
to try to build some tools
and involve the community.

00:29:25.730 --> 00:29:26.970
So it's starting.

00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:29.190
It's still very hard
to put all of that

00:29:29.190 --> 00:29:32.860
together because each
crisis is different.

00:29:32.860 --> 00:29:34.870
There's also the
notion of, there's

00:29:34.870 --> 00:29:37.220
a group here I
put-- Crisis Common.

00:29:37.220 --> 00:29:38.680
And they do some crisis camp.

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:41.390
Something happens, and
everyone gathers in a place

00:29:41.390 --> 00:29:44.337
and, depending on your skill,
you can help and et cetera.

00:29:44.337 --> 00:29:45.920
So in that situation
there's a lot of,

00:29:45.920 --> 00:29:47.420
sometimes you end
up doing something

00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:48.520
that someone else did.

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:51.010
It's not the most efficient
part, but the point at the end

00:29:51.010 --> 00:29:52.880
is just to be able to
do a task and if it

00:29:52.880 --> 00:29:57.230
was done like two times, then
it's not the end of the world.

00:29:57.230 --> 00:29:59.800
So there's some community
that are growing and growing.

00:29:59.800 --> 00:30:01.460
So this Crisis
Mapper, for example,

00:30:01.460 --> 00:30:03.570
has a conference every
year, bringing together

00:30:03.570 --> 00:30:06.310
people that are doing
mapping in crisis.

00:30:06.310 --> 00:30:09.510
So little by little, when
you're talking about the--

00:30:09.510 --> 00:30:11.560
it's almost, what
is needed where

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:13.510
and the coordination
between organizations.

00:30:13.510 --> 00:30:16.140
It's something that is
still a very big struggle.

00:30:16.140 --> 00:30:19.470
How do we know that there's
some water that is needed here,

00:30:19.470 --> 00:30:20.880
and the Red Cross
is going there,

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:23.080
but another organization
is also going there,

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:25.050
and how do you
coordinate all of that,

00:30:25.050 --> 00:30:27.125
is something that
is still very hard.

00:30:30.240 --> 00:30:31.011
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:31.011 --> 00:30:32.010
Thank you for your talk.

00:30:32.010 --> 00:30:33.700
It was really good.

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:35.390
My question is
about the offline.

00:30:35.390 --> 00:30:38.660
You mentioned one of the things
you're tackling now is offline.

00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:41.970
I come from Kenya and we
had post-election violence

00:30:41.970 --> 00:30:45.320
in 2007 and 2008,
around that time,

00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:48.010
and Ushahidi did a lot
of work during that time.

00:30:48.010 --> 00:30:51.460
And because a lot of
people didn't have access

00:30:51.460 --> 00:30:54.400
to smartphones at the time and
were just using feature phones,

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:57.890
they used SMS as a tool
to be able to do that.

00:30:57.890 --> 00:31:01.150
And I think they worked with
frontlineSMS, they're called.

00:31:01.150 --> 00:31:04.219
Have you explored that and what
has your experience been if so?

00:31:04.219 --> 00:31:05.760
ALICE BONHOMME-BIAIS:
Yeah, so that's

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:09.110
some discussion we have
regularly about how much

00:31:09.110 --> 00:31:10.620
to add SMS.

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:14.580
So Person Finder, we actually
added during Yolanda.

00:31:14.580 --> 00:31:16.050
We added an SMS feature.

00:31:16.050 --> 00:31:17.540
So we do a lot of
sometimes coding

00:31:17.540 --> 00:31:19.000
on the fly when
something happens,

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.030
when there's a specific need.

00:31:21.030 --> 00:31:25.450
And Typhoon Yolanda was an
example where the internet

00:31:25.450 --> 00:31:29.250
penetration was not so high,
but with the devastation

00:31:29.250 --> 00:31:32.960
it was much harder for people
to have access to the internet.

00:31:32.960 --> 00:31:37.700
And so we launched Person Finder
and we added a feature for SMS

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:38.690
to Person Finder.

00:31:42.492 --> 00:31:44.700
So this is definitely a use
case that we have in mind

00:31:44.700 --> 00:31:45.700
and how to best use.

00:31:45.700 --> 00:31:50.920
We also, I personally think,
that for us, having some APIs

00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:53.530
and having some local
groups know better

00:31:53.530 --> 00:31:56.110
how to interface the
data coming from this API

00:31:56.110 --> 00:31:58.590
to the local community
were almost be the best.

00:31:58.590 --> 00:32:02.870
You can imagine also radio
is big in these places.

00:32:02.870 --> 00:32:05.430
So having some local
groups that will

00:32:05.430 --> 00:32:08.540
do this bridge in
between the two.

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:11.630
But I know Ushahidi has
been doing amazing work,

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:15.880
and it started with the
riots in Kenya in 2008.

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:20.500
So we don't have necessarily
SMS capabilities for everything,

00:32:20.500 --> 00:32:25.242
but we try to piggyback as much
as we can on existing projects.

00:32:25.242 --> 00:32:26.790
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
know frontlineSMS

00:32:26.790 --> 00:32:28.640
is a good API for that.

00:32:28.640 --> 00:32:29.900
So, thank you.

00:32:29.900 --> 00:32:31.609
ALICE BONHOMME-BIAIS: Thanks.

00:32:31.609 --> 00:32:32.650
AUDIENCE: Good afternoon.

00:32:32.650 --> 00:32:34.020
I'm Victoria.

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:35.270
Thank you for your talk.

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:37.900
I was wondering
how do you manage

00:32:37.900 --> 00:32:39.380
the teams that work on this?

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:42.310
And how is it different
to manage a team

00:32:42.310 --> 00:32:44.660
when there's a crisis situation?

00:32:44.660 --> 00:32:46.275
When the stress
levels are high, what

00:32:46.275 --> 00:32:49.750
do you do differently to manage
so things are still efficient?

00:32:49.750 --> 00:32:51.960
ALICE BONHOMME-BIAIS: So
that's a good question.

00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:54.390
Because there's stress, but
when something happens-- so,

00:32:54.390 --> 00:32:58.350
in four years it changed a lot.

00:32:58.350 --> 00:33:01.890
From when we initially
created the team,

00:33:01.890 --> 00:33:03.393
it was something
happened, everyone

00:33:03.393 --> 00:33:05.226
was running like crazy,
we're not organized,

00:33:05.226 --> 00:33:09.270
we were just coding all over.

00:33:09.270 --> 00:33:11.070
And now we're much
more organized.

00:33:11.070 --> 00:33:14.872
So for example, we have
people on pager rotation.

00:33:14.872 --> 00:33:16.330
So when something
happens, it's not

00:33:16.330 --> 00:33:17.900
the entire team
that does something.

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:20.620
So you can keep
working on writing

00:33:20.620 --> 00:33:23.240
tools that will help you
automate most of the things

00:33:23.240 --> 00:33:23.804
that you do.

00:33:23.804 --> 00:33:25.470
Eventually, it would
be great if we just

00:33:25.470 --> 00:33:28.240
have tools and people
use directly the tools

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:30.220
and we don't need to do
something special when

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:32.370
something happens.

00:33:32.370 --> 00:33:36.150
So we also have people
in the team that are here

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:38.090
because they want to
work on crisis response,

00:33:38.090 --> 00:33:40.350
so they're very dedicated.

00:33:40.350 --> 00:33:42.500
I am actually not
managing the team.

00:33:42.500 --> 00:33:44.790
I'm an engineer on the team.

00:33:44.790 --> 00:33:47.520
And the team grew,
so at the beginning,

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:49.830
I think that plays
well to the team,

00:33:49.830 --> 00:33:55.350
is people-- you do whatever
it takes to bring tools

00:33:55.350 --> 00:33:57.460
or to launch something
that will help people.

00:33:57.460 --> 00:34:02.210
If that means that you have
to spend some time manually

00:34:02.210 --> 00:34:05.190
populating a spreadsheet because
that's the only thing that

00:34:05.190 --> 00:34:07.800
will be possible,
then you do it.

00:34:07.800 --> 00:34:11.489
I think we learned how to
manage the stress of working

00:34:11.489 --> 00:34:13.050
on a topic that is hard.

00:34:13.050 --> 00:34:16.110
So for me personally, for
example, sometimes I just

00:34:16.110 --> 00:34:18.909
work on-- we need to
launch Person Finder,

00:34:18.909 --> 00:34:21.070
we need to enable some SMS.

00:34:21.070 --> 00:34:23.770
I don't necessarily
pay a lot of attention

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:25.230
to the situation on the ground.

00:34:25.230 --> 00:34:27.830
Otherwise, that's just going
to disturb me too much.

00:34:27.830 --> 00:34:32.150
So my husband sometimes tells
me, so you know, what happened?

00:34:32.150 --> 00:34:32.985
And I cannot say.

00:34:32.985 --> 00:34:34.360
I say, we launched
Person Finder.

00:34:34.360 --> 00:34:35.068
We're doing that.

00:34:35.068 --> 00:34:38.770
I cannot tell you exactly
what's going on the ground.

00:34:38.770 --> 00:34:42.070
That's some other people on the
team that are working on that.

00:34:42.070 --> 00:34:44.389
But it's a way, I think
also, to protect myself,

00:34:44.389 --> 00:34:49.420
otherwise it's some really
hard situation to work with.

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:53.070
And it's a lot of chat, lot
of everything goes very fast.

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:55.570
So we have a common chat
room and everyone jumps in.

00:34:55.570 --> 00:34:58.520
And I should have mentioned--
so we are a small team,

00:34:58.520 --> 00:35:03.300
but we work a lot with Google
offices all over the world.

00:35:03.300 --> 00:35:04.800
So for example, for
the Philippines,

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:06.383
we worked with people
from the region.

00:35:06.383 --> 00:35:07.930
Some people in India helped.

00:35:07.930 --> 00:35:09.999
So each time we work
with the local expertise.

00:35:09.999 --> 00:35:11.540
They know what's
going on the ground.

00:35:11.540 --> 00:35:15.060
We bring the technological
side and we discuss together.

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:16.800
Even if we never met
in person, there's

00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:19.424
some people I always spent a lot
of time talking to each other.

00:35:19.424 --> 00:35:20.960
I never met the person.

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:23.959
Does that answer your question?

00:35:23.959 --> 00:35:24.500
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:26.292
Thank you for talk.

00:35:26.292 --> 00:35:27.750
This was a really
interesting talk,

00:35:27.750 --> 00:35:29.610
and I think it brings
a lot of questions

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:32.555
to the surface about
public versus private.

00:35:32.555 --> 00:35:34.680
It's different in the case
of international crisis.

00:35:34.680 --> 00:35:37.914
But particularly for the
domestic crises like Sandy,

00:35:37.914 --> 00:35:39.330
it seems like your
team and Google

00:35:39.330 --> 00:35:44.840
are filling a void where the
public sector has fallen short.

00:35:44.840 --> 00:35:48.680
Because they don't seem to
be up to date on technology

00:35:48.680 --> 00:35:51.720
and using it for good purposes.

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:54.680
That's great for now.

00:35:54.680 --> 00:35:57.350
There are some conflict
of interests in the way.

00:35:57.350 --> 00:35:59.550
Do we want government
to do this?

00:35:59.550 --> 00:36:01.150
Do we want Google to do this?

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:02.820
I'm sure your team
and the company

00:36:02.820 --> 00:36:05.612
